{"parentUuid":"dc4c7db0-549b-4f61-ab44-53f6ad8f93e7","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ac7c99e6fe1d41e66","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01EZHd25Ld7dfH8hr6WTpCWv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CWaqqKjPQoL7AR6kJ4nWLa","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"Does RL really incentivize reasoning capacity beyond the base model Yue 2025"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6102,"cache_read_input_tokens":6425,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6102,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":8442}}},"requestId":"req_011CcG28bQHcEs8aK8XDT5iL","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"e90e0fee-c3c2-4dee-8110-d9e9d9da114a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:52.037Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"d42fe5a9-4630-478c-b034-d83483dc97a0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"ac7c99e6fe1d41e66","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QRif22ukDLHgAGJpar6dqV","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Darwin Godel Machine self-improve agent code not foundation model frozen\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Self-Improving AI: Darwin Gödel Machine Evolves Code\",\"url\":\"https://www.ikangai.com/self-improving-ai-darwin-godel-machine-evolves-code/\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine: Self-Improving AI Agents - AI Papers Academy\",\"url\":\"https://aipapersacademy.com/darwin-godel-machine/\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine — a self improving AI? | by Anatol Wegner | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@AIchats/darwin-g%C3%B6del-machines-a-self-improving-ai-8b5074de161a\"},{\"title\":\"[2505.22954] Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954\"},{\"title\":\"The Darwin Gödel Machine: AI that improves itself by rewriting its own code\",\"url\":\"https://sakana.ai/dgm/\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine - by Grigory Sapunov - Gonzo ML\",\"url\":\"https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/darwin-godel-machine\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pUpzQZTvGY\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - jennyzzt/dgm: Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/jennyzzt/dgm\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what the Darwin Gödel Machine does regarding self-improvement, code modification, and its relationship with frozen foundation models:\n\n## Self-Improvement Through Code Modification\n\nThe Darwin Gödel Machine (DGM) is a self-improving system that iteratively modifies its own code (thereby also improving its ability to modify its own codebase) and empirically validates each change using coding benchmarks. The system treats its own source code as mutable genetic material.\n\n## Frozen Foundation Models Constraint\n\nThe DGM modifies only the \"scaffolding\" around frozen foundation models rather than the models themselves. The use of frozen FMs enables the system to concentrate on innovating the design and workflows of the coding agents, rather than undertaking the computationally intensive task of retraining the FMs themselves.\n\n## Performance Results\n\nThe DGM automatically improves its coding capabilities (e.g., better code editing tools, long-context window management, peer-review mechanisms), increasing performance on SWE-bench from 20.0% to 50.0%, and on Polyglot from 14.2% to 30.7%.\n\n## Population-Based Evolution\n\nThe system maintains an ever-growing \"archive\" of coding agents—think of it as a population of digital organisms, each with slightly different capabilities. When tasked with self-improvement, the DGM selects promising candidates from this archive, modifies their code, and tests the results on coding benchmarks.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"ffdb5f9a-703a-40ab-b2d9-8c6525bc3323","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:57.291Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Darwin Godel Machine self-improve agent code not foundation model frozen","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Epx6UtryBWxFSY4zFWw62D","content":[{"title":"Self-Improving AI: Darwin Gödel Machine Evolves Code","url":"https://www.ikangai.com/self-improving-ai-darwin-godel-machine-evolves-code/"},{"title":"Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine: Self-Improving AI Agents - AI Papers Academy","url":"https://aipapersacademy.com/darwin-godel-machine/"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine — a self improving AI? | by Anatol Wegner | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@AIchats/darwin-g%C3%B6del-machines-a-self-improving-ai-8b5074de161a"},{"title":"[2505.22954] Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954"},{"title":"The Darwin Gödel Machine: AI that improves itself by rewriting its own code","url":"https://sakana.ai/dgm/"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine - by Grigory Sapunov - Gonzo ML","url":"https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/darwin-godel-machine"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pUpzQZTvGY"},{"title":"GitHub - jennyzzt/dgm: Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/jennyzzt/dgm"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what the Darwin Gödel Machine does regarding self-improvement, code modification, and its relationship with frozen foundation models:\n\n## Self-Improvement Through Code Modification\n\nThe Darwin Gödel Machine (DGM) is a self-improving system that iteratively modifies its own code (thereby also improving its ability to modify its own codebase) and empirically validates each change using coding benchmarks. The system treats its own source code as mutable genetic material.\n\n## Frozen Foundation Models Constraint\n\nThe DGM modifies only the \"scaffolding\" around frozen foundation models rather than the models themselves. The use of frozen FMs enables the system to concentrate on innovating the design and workflows of the coding agents, rather than undertaking the computationally intensive task of retraining the FMs themselves.\n\n## Performance Results\n\nThe DGM automatically improves its coding capabilities (e.g., better code editing tools, long-context window management, peer-review mechanisms), increasing performance on SWE-bench from 20.0% to 50.0%, and on Polyglot from 14.2% to 30.7%.\n\n## Population-Based Evolution\n\nThe system maintains an ever-growing \"archive\" of coding agents—think of it as a population of digital organisms, each with slightly different capabilities. When tasked with self-improvement, the DGM selects promising candidates from this archive, modifies their code, and tests the results on coding benchmarks."],"durationSeconds":6.628992583001033,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d42fe5a9-4630-478c-b034-d83483dc97a0","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"dc4c7db0-549b-4f61-ab44-53f6ad8f93e7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"ac7c99e6fe1d41e66","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014tVE8wCNaS45G9G6a27szD","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"STOP self-taught optimizer language model held fixed scaffolding program\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2310.02304\"},{\"title\":\"The Dawn of Recursive Intelligence: Microsoft’s Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP) Breaks New Ground | by Ahmed Ghazouani | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@nibniw/the-dawn-of-recursive-intelligence-microsofts-self-taught-optimizer-stop-breaks-new-ground-96a562c10de3\"},{\"title\":\"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.02304\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - microsoft/stop: Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/microsoft/stop\"},{\"title\":\"Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"http://opt-ml.org/papers/2023/paper21.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://blog.athina.ai/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation - Microsoft Research\",\"url\":\"https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation/\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1gkePTsAWf\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation | AI Research Paper Details\",\"url\":\"https://www.aimodels.fyi/papers/arxiv/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about STOP (Self-Taught Optimizer):\n\n## Overview\n\nSTOP is a method in which code that applies a language model to improve arbitrary solutions is applied recursively to improve itself. The system was developed through a collaboration between Microsoft and Stanford University.\n\n## Scaffolding Programs\n\nScaffolding programs are typically written in a programming language such as Python. For any distribution over optimization problems and any fixed language model, the design of a scaffolding program is itself an optimization problem.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThe approach begins with an initial seed 'improver' scaffolding program that uses the language model to improve a solution to some downstream task. A seed \"improver\" improves an input program according to a given utility function by querying a language model several times and returning the best solution, and when this seed improver is run to improve itself, the resulting improved improver generates programs with significantly better performance than its seed improver.\n\n## Key Features\n\nSince the language models themselves are not altered, this is not full recursive self-improvement, but it demonstrates that a modern language model like GPT-4 is capable of writing code that can call itself to improve itself. STOP uses strategies like beam search, genetic algorithms, and simulated annealing, all directed by the language model's suggestions.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b7eec026-c69f-4ba1-b4a8-76b531568219","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:59.127Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"STOP self-taught optimizer language model held fixed scaffolding program","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01PvzSdUSETXcwsBibT3eDvh","content":[{"title":"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2310.02304"},{"title":"The Dawn of Recursive Intelligence: Microsoft’s Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP) Breaks New Ground | by Ahmed Ghazouani | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@nibniw/the-dawn-of-recursive-intelligence-microsofts-self-taught-optimizer-stop-breaks-new-ground-96a562c10de3"},{"title":"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.02304"},{"title":"GitHub - microsoft/stop: Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/microsoft/stop"},{"title":"Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"http://opt-ml.org/papers/2023/paper21.pdf"},{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://blog.athina.ai/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation"},{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation - Microsoft Research","url":"https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation/"},{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1gkePTsAWf"},{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation | AI Research Paper Details","url":"https://www.aimodels.fyi/papers/arxiv/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about STOP (Self-Taught Optimizer):\n\n## Overview\n\nSTOP is a method in which code that applies a language model to improve arbitrary solutions is applied recursively to improve itself. The system was developed through a collaboration between Microsoft and Stanford University.\n\n## Scaffolding Programs\n\nScaffolding programs are typically written in a programming language such as Python. For any distribution over optimization problems and any fixed language model, the design of a scaffolding program is itself an optimization problem.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThe approach begins with an initial seed 'improver' scaffolding program that uses the language model to improve a solution to some downstream task. A seed \"improver\" improves an input program according to a given utility function by querying a language model several times and returning the best solution, and when this seed improver is run to improve itself, the resulting improved improver generates programs with significantly better performance than its seed improver.\n\n## Key Features\n\nSince the language models themselves are not altered, this is not full recursive self-improvement, but it demonstrates that a modern language model like GPT-4 is capable of writing code that can call itself to improve itself. STOP uses strategies like beam search, genetic algorithms, and simulated annealing, all directed by the language model's suggestions."],"durationSeconds":7.094770665999502,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"dc4c7db0-549b-4f61-ab44-53f6ad8f93e7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"e90e0fee-c3c2-4dee-8110-d9e9d9da114a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"ac7c99e6fe1d41e66","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CWaqqKjPQoL7AR6kJ4nWLa","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Does RL really incentivize reasoning capacity beyond the base model Yue 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"November 25, 2025 Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.13837\"},{\"title\":\"[2504.13837] Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.13837\"},{\"title\":\"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?\",\"url\":\"https://bibbase.org/network/publication/yue-chen-lu-zhao-wang-yue-song-huang-doesreinforcementlearningreallyincentivizereasoningcapacityinllmsbeyondthebasemodel-2025\"},{\"title\":\"[Paper Note] Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?, Yang Yue+, NeurIPS'25, 2025.04 · Issue #3589 · AkihikoWatanabe/paper_notes\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/AkihikoWatanabe/paper_notes/issues/3589\"},{\"title\":\"NeurIPS Poster Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?\",\"url\":\"https://neurips.cc/virtual/2025/poster/119944\"},{\"title\":\"Grounded Reinforcement Learning for Visual Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.23678\"},{\"title\":\"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4OsgYD7em5\"},{\"title\":\"ICML Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?\",\"url\":\"https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/52367\"},{\"title\":\"New Skills or Sharper Primitives? A Probabilistic Perspective on the Emergence of Reasoning in RLVR\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.08281\"},{\"title\":\"RL Grokking Recipe: How Does RL Unlock and Transfer New Algorithms in LLMs?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.21016\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found the relevant paper by Yang Yue and colleagues from 2025. Here's what the research shows:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nThe current training setup does not elicit fundamentally new reasoning patterns. While RLVR-trained models outperform their base models at small k (e.g., k = 1), the base models achieve a higher pass@k score when k is large.\n\nThe paper conducts systematic and rigorous experiments to show that not only reflective behaviors but all reasoning paths are already embedded in the base model. Coverage and perplexity analyses show that the observed reasoning abilities originate from and are bounded by the base model.\n\n## Broader Implications\n\nThe findings suggest that current RLVR methods have not yet realized the potential of RL to elicit truly novel reasoning abilities in LLMs. This highlights the need for improved RL paradigms, such as continual scaling and multi-turn agent-environment interaction, to unlock this potential.\n\nNotably, distillation can introduce new reasoning patterns from the teacher and genuinely expand the model's reasoning capabilities, suggesting alternative approaches may be more effective than current RLVR methods.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"79e9c7f4-ec8e-4ec0-a0e9-091c74dc9b23","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:59.186Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Does RL really incentivize reasoning capacity beyond the base model Yue 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01CGFijLkPp5WiyEKgcyk2ox","content":[{"title":"November 25, 2025 Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.13837"},{"title":"[2504.13837] Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.13837"},{"title":"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?","url":"https://bibbase.org/network/publication/yue-chen-lu-zhao-wang-yue-song-huang-doesreinforcementlearningreallyincentivizereasoningcapacityinllmsbeyondthebasemodel-2025"},{"title":"[Paper Note] Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?, Yang Yue+, NeurIPS'25, 2025.04 · Issue #3589 · AkihikoWatanabe/paper_notes","url":"https://github.com/AkihikoWatanabe/paper_notes/issues/3589"},{"title":"NeurIPS Poster Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?","url":"https://neurips.cc/virtual/2025/poster/119944"},{"title":"Grounded Reinforcement Learning for Visual Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.23678"},{"title":"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4OsgYD7em5"},{"title":"ICML Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?","url":"https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/52367"},{"title":"New Skills or Sharper Primitives? A Probabilistic Perspective on the Emergence of Reasoning in RLVR","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.08281"},{"title":"RL Grokking Recipe: How Does RL Unlock and Transfer New Algorithms in LLMs?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.21016"}]},"Based on the search results, I found the relevant paper by Yang Yue and colleagues from 2025. Here's what the research shows:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nThe current training setup does not elicit fundamentally new reasoning patterns. While RLVR-trained models outperform their base models at small k (e.g., k = 1), the base models achieve a higher pass@k score when k is large.\n\nThe paper conducts systematic and rigorous experiments to show that not only reflective behaviors but all reasoning paths are already embedded in the base model. Coverage and perplexity analyses show that the observed reasoning abilities originate from and are bounded by the base model.\n\n## Broader Implications\n\nThe findings suggest that current RLVR methods have not yet realized the potential of RL to elicit truly novel reasoning abilities in LLMs. This highlights the need for improved RL paradigms, such as continual scaling and multi-turn agent-environment interaction, to unlock this potential.\n\nNotably, distillation can introduce new reasoning patterns from the teacher and genuinely expand the model's reasoning capabilities, suggesting alternative approaches may be more effective than current RLVR methods."],"durationSeconds":6.934370500000194,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e90e0fee-c3c2-4dee-8110-d9e9d9da114a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"f457fc1a-fad1-4a4d-9ee1-66ba81d95869","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"ac7c99e6fe1d41e66","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013KWPKxRGwunFNYv9yxSMnG","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AlphaEvolve ensemble Gemini base models evolutionary search programs\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve | AI Wiki\",\"url\":\"https://aiwiki.ai/wiki/alphaevolve\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/392736011_AlphaEvolve_A_coding_agent_for_scientific_and_algorithmic_discovery\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AlphaEvolve\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - algorithmicsuperintelligence/openevolve: Open-source implementation of AlphaEvolve · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/algorithmicsuperintelligence/openevolve\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve on Google Cloud | Google Cloud Blog\",\"url\":\"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/alphaevolve-on-google-cloud/\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve - by Grigory Sapunov - Gonzo ML - Substack\",\"url\":\"https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/alphaevolve\"},{\"title\":\"Accelerate R&D with Co-Scientist and AlphaEvolve agents | Gemini Enterprise | Google Cloud Documentation\",\"url\":\"https://docs.cloud.google.com/gemini/enterprise/docs/co-scientist-and-alphaevolve\"},{\"title\":\"MadEvolve: Evolutionary Optimization of Cosmological Algorithms with Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.15951\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve:\n\n## Overview\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary coding agent developed by Google DeepMind and announced on May 14, 2025. The system uses an ensemble of Gemini large language models paired with automated evaluators and an evolutionary search framework to discover and optimize algorithms across mathematics, hardware design, and computing infrastructure.\n\n## Ensemble of Gemini Models\n\nAlphaEvolve utilizes a combination of Gemini 2.0 Flash and Gemini 2.0 Pro, which allows balancing computational throughput with the quality of generated solutions. Gemini 2.0 Flash, with its lower latency, enables a higher rate of candidate generation, while Gemini 2.0 Pro, possessing greater capabilities, provides occasional, higher-quality suggestions that can significantly advance the evolutionary search.\n\n## Evolutionary Search Programs\n\nRather than rewriting entire programs from scratch each iteration, the system makes targeted edits, which preserves working structure while exploring variations. AlphaEvolve treats the LLM as an intelligent mutation operator, and because Gemini models are trained on broad natural language and code, they implicitly know standard genetic operators (crossover, mutation, selection).\n\n## Key Applications\n\nAlphaEvolve enhanced the efficiency of Google's data centers, chip design and AI training processes, and has also helped design faster matrix multiplication algorithms and find new solutions to open mathematical problems.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"3ec2565f-63f3-4543-8d3d-17ffebcb3cc5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:01.999Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"AlphaEvolve ensemble Gemini base models evolutionary search programs","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Dpx3Zk5S2tL9PvV745gp1y","content":[{"title":"AlphaEvolve | AI Wiki","url":"https://aiwiki.ai/wiki/alphaevolve"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery","url":"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf"},{"title":"(PDF) AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/392736011_AlphaEvolve_A_coding_agent_for_scientific_and_algorithmic_discovery"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AlphaEvolve"},{"title":"GitHub - algorithmicsuperintelligence/openevolve: Open-source implementation of AlphaEvolve · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/algorithmicsuperintelligence/openevolve"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve on Google Cloud | Google Cloud Blog","url":"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/alphaevolve-on-google-cloud/"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve - by Grigory Sapunov - Gonzo ML - Substack","url":"https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/alphaevolve"},{"title":"Accelerate R&D with Co-Scientist and AlphaEvolve agents | Gemini Enterprise | Google Cloud Documentation","url":"https://docs.cloud.google.com/gemini/enterprise/docs/co-scientist-and-alphaevolve"},{"title":"MadEvolve: Evolutionary Optimization of Cosmological Algorithms with Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.15951"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve:\n\n## Overview\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary coding agent developed by Google DeepMind and announced on May 14, 2025. The system uses an ensemble of Gemini large language models paired with automated evaluators and an evolutionary search framework to discover and optimize algorithms across mathematics, hardware design, and computing infrastructure.\n\n## Ensemble of Gemini Models\n\nAlphaEvolve utilizes a combination of Gemini 2.0 Flash and Gemini 2.0 Pro, which allows balancing computational throughput with the quality of generated solutions. Gemini 2.0 Flash, with its lower latency, enables a higher rate of candidate generation, while Gemini 2.0 Pro, possessing greater capabilities, provides occasional, higher-quality suggestions that can significantly advance the evolutionary search.\n\n## Evolutionary Search Programs\n\nRather than rewriting entire programs from scratch each iteration, the system makes targeted edits, which preserves working structure while exploring variations. AlphaEvolve treats the LLM as an intelligent mutation operator, and because Gemini models are trained on broad natural language and code, they implicitly know standard genetic operators (crossover, mutation, selection).\n\n## Key Applications\n\nAlphaEvolve enhanced the efficiency of Google's data centers, chip design and AI training processes, and has also helped design faster matrix multiplication algorithms and find new solutions to open mathematical problems."],"durationSeconds":10.544304540999233,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f457fc1a-fad1-4a4d-9ee1-66ba81d95869","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
